useState vs AsyncStorage (200–300 words)

In this To-Do List project, I used both useState and AsyncStorage, and each serves a different purpose.
 useState is a React Hook used to store and manage data while the application is running. 
 It allows the app to update the user interface whenever the data changes. 
 For example, when I add a new task, delete a task, mark a task as completed, or change the filter, 
 the useState hook updates the task list immediately without refreshing the application. However, 
 the data stored in useState exists only while the app is open. If the application is closed, the data stored in useState is lost.

AsyncStorage, on the other hand, is used for permanent local storage. It stores data on the device so that
 it remains available even after the application is closed or restarted. In this project, I used AsyncStorage
  to save the task list whenever changes were made. When the app starts again, the saved tasks are loaded from 
  AsyncStorage and displayed automatically. This gives the user a better experience because they do not lose their tasks
   after reopening the app.

In summary, useState is used for temporary state management during the app's execution, while AsyncStorage is used for
 persistent storage that keeps data available across app sessions. Both technologies work together in this 
 project: useState provides fast and responsive updates to the interface, and AsyncStorage ensures that the user's tasks
  are safely stored and restored whenever the application is reopened.